    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Business Days Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Select a start date and an end date using the date pickers. The calculator instantly counts the number of business days (Monday through Friday) between the two dates, excluding weekends. It also shows the total calendar days, the number of weekend days, and the duration in weeks. This makes it easy to convert between business days and calendar days for any date range.
      </p>
      <p>
        The calculator uses start-inclusive, end-exclusive counting. This means if your start date is a Monday and your end date is the following Monday, the result is 5 business days (the five weekdays of that week). This is the standard convention used in most business and legal contexts.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Why Business Day Calculations Matter</h2>
      <p>
        Many professional and legal processes operate on business day timelines. Bank transfers typically process within 1 to 3 business days. Shipping services quote delivery windows in business days. Legal filing deadlines, regulatory response periods, and contractual notice requirements are frequently specified in business days. Using calendar days instead of business days in these situations can lead to costly errors.
      </p>

      <h3>Financial and Banking Timelines</h3>
      <p>
        Banks and financial institutions process most transactions only on business days. ACH transfers take 1 to 3 business days. Wire transfers are completed within 1 business day. Credit card disputes have resolution deadlines measured in business days. Understanding the distinction helps you plan cash flow and avoid late payments or penalties from miscounting days.
      </p>

      <h3>Project Management</h3>
      <p>
        Project timelines are almost always expressed in business days because team members work on weekdays. A task estimated at 10 business days translates to two full calendar weeks. When building a project schedule, converting between business and calendar days ensures accurate deadline setting. This calculator eliminates the mental math of counting weekdays on a calendar.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How are business days calculated?</h3>
      <p>
        Business days are weekdays from Monday through Friday. The calculator counts every day between your start and end dates and excludes Saturdays and Sundays.
      </p>

      <h3>Does the calculator exclude public holidays?</h3>
      <p>
        The basic calculation excludes only weekends. Public holidays vary by country, state, and employer. For the most accurate count, subtract any holidays that fall within your range from the result.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between business days and calendar days?</h3>
      <p>
        Calendar days count every day including weekends and holidays. Business days count only weekdays. A 7-calendar-day week contains 5 business days.
      </p>

      <h3>Why do I need to know the number of business days?</h3>
      <p>
        Many deadlines, shipping estimates, legal timelines, and payment terms are expressed in business days. Confusing business days with calendar days can cause you to miss deadlines or set incorrect expectations.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I calculate a future date from business days?</h3>
      <p>
        Count forward through weekdays only. For example, 10 business days from a Monday is two weeks later. Enter different end dates in this calculator to find the one that gives you the business day count you need.
      </p>

